The Bone House is still fascinating after 100 years. Take a look at the interiors from Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the staircase resembles the backbone of a dinosaur, and the balconies are open to a fish mouth.
Such is the Casa Batlló in Barcelona by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
The house earned the house from the locals the nickname the Bone House thanks to its organic shapes.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, fragments of tiles and mosaics, a scales-like facade and ubiquitous soft curves are all typical of the Art Nouveau by Antoni Gaudi.
The front of the house plays out the dreamy lines, tender colours and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
In detailed observations, you can see the geometricity, rhythm and precisely thought-out order.
At night, the whole facade of the houses is even more dramatic, illuminated to make the impression of colouring a bit more amplified.
The culling and twisting of shapes appears equally in the interiors.
The wood in the waves replicates the window frames, the railing, the decorative elements of the door, the peepholes and the molders.
Batlló house, which is located in the Eixample district on the bustling shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43, was created by the reconstruction of the 1877 house by architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
Reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on demolishing the old structure and building a brand new one, but soon embraced Gaudí's idea of an unusual and cheaper rebuilding.
But the Casa Batlló apartment house was not proposed by Antoni Gaudí himself.
It was co-operated by architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on his design board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the owner of the property were created and the use of the mosaic on the facade were created.
A number of other creators and artists also worked on the facade.
Working together on the designs of the Casa Batlló house started with Jujol's successful collaboration with Gaudi.
Yujol participated in the construction of Gaudí's house Casa Milá as well as Park Güell, which houses Gaudi's other works.
From the locals, the house soon after its completion, thanks to its organic shapes, earned the nickname "Dench of Bones."
Others, for the specific mechanism of opening the windows, began to call it a "simmer house."
It is also said that the sword of St. George, the patron saint of Catalonia, is represented at the top of the structure.
The hidden religious motifs also contain other sculptural elements of the building.
Gaudí designed for his time for his time a unique system of central heating with ventilation vents and typical chimneys.
Bizarre may seem to be their forty-five-degree gradient.
In the creation of Gaudí absolutely did not respect the building regulations of the time and did not let them be constrained.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained a building permit from the city, but the data provided by him were so vague that two years later, when the city council was horrified by the result and asked for redress.
Councillors were concerned, for example, that the construction interfered with the Pillar and the public sidewalk.
There was never a correction, on the contrary: only fifteen days after the city's call to the city district, Josep Batlló applied (and successfully obtained) permission to lease the two tallest floors of the building.
The owner himself moved into the lower levels.
The second-floet gallery featured a formal salon and a bedroom and a private part of the apartment on the third floor.
The ground floor was leased to jewellery.
The entire six-storey house is intersected by a staircase to climb up to the rooftop terrace itself.
The essential elements of the redevelopment were the abolition of all the right angles and straight lines and their replacement with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connecting the space.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the parlour doors, and the larger company can communicate comfortably without at the same time preserving the privacy needed for more intimate interviews.
The house with Gaudí's reconstruction was also given an unconventional roofing and two extra floors.
The Gaudi game with the light, blue and white glazed tiles, which is lined with the inner courtyard, and the skylights, are also impressive.
The game of two colours adds maximum light to all floors of the house.
Simply betting on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which absorbs the sun's rays.
The house Casa Batlló, which was included in the Unesco World Heritage Fund in 2005, can be visited by anyone.
On the first floor of the house, the spaciousest and most aloatan apartment is made available to the public.
The owners did not opt for the move until 2002, to mark the 100th anniversary of the famous creator's birth.
They remained at the tours, finding that it was a very advantageous undertaking and, in addition, they extended the tours to include joint and attic spaces, including the roof terrace.
Admission to the monument is by no means insignificant, at €16.50 and students, pensioners, groups and tourist card holders have a 20 percent discount.
The sum greatly exceeds the price of admission to other Gaudí's buildings in the city.
