Men who have a finger longer than a ring finger are at a lesser risk of getting prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British Cancer Journal.
It may be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the finger can serve as a simple test of the risk of prostate cancer, especially for men under 60, especially for men under 60," said co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
