In the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in the UK tracked more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients and, at the same time, over three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had a index finger on their right hand shorter than the ring finger.
They were as likely to be prostate cancer as for 19 percent whose fingers were the same length.
However, in the case of those with a finger longer than a ring finger, this risk dropped by 33 percent, for men up to sixty, the decline was even 87 per cent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers in question - shaped in the prenatal period - appears to reflect the different levels of the sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the womb.
Less testosterone matches a longer index finger.
