Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
The European Commission, for example, saw 2009 as a reference: international funding has been preserved and it adds 150 million to it for a three-year fast start funding title.
Other countries have selected similar references with annual payment terms or terms at the level of public aid for development.
By contrast, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" of 2010 is 'new and additional'.
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous periods or to the global level of Public Aid for the Development of d'Aide publique au développement.
In particular, the total amount of support for France towards developing countries may remain constant (or even reduced), it is to honour its commitment to "new and additional funding...
Another crucial element is the distribution of donations and loans.
There is no rule yet, and each chooses their own method of calculation.
Some, such as. France, they are considering that 1€ borrowed is equal to 1€ donated.
Evidently, this is hard to prove: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be substantiated for some investments that are profitable (often to be projects linked to a reduction in emissions, consisting of more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro that we receive as the equivalent of one euro we give... , we should not understand it as a loan price for the creditor country (i.e. the equivalent of the interest rate).
But France can only make such a justification: "compensating" its commitment of €420 million, of which 91.5% is the loan (€389.8 million) and 8.5% of donations (€36.11 million) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union that uses a loan on such a scale.
Germany has requested 46% of there, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) abide by their commitments with 100% of their gifts.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union gives €1 to its promise in satisfaction, France will only give 10 centims and consider this effort to be comparable.
A beautiful juggler piece!
To summarise, in its financing of the "fast start" France operates with a double cheat: on the one hand, the development of the share over time and, on the other, with a real financial burden.
Although it is spending only €36.1 million, he can convince to spend €420 million "new and additional" in connection with her promises.
The manipulation of the Chancellor of the Exchequer (because it seems that although it is Bercy who made such decisions) could have a double negative impact, at the same time within the EU (why would the Member States continue to donate when just to lend?) and in the negotiations, because developing countries are not entirely naive...
The early financing chapter is just a small question, relatively short-term, in relation to a series of climate discussions.
But it could be a grain of sand in an enormous machine like the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that's not the case for us.
Whatever this is, it is essential to draw on the lessons of this first year of early funding.
First, France should announce a change in its way of keeping the accounting records for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and decency and fairness to other European Union countries.
But above all, France should avoid a debate on deposits in long-term financing (another crucial chapter currently discussed): we will not escape the issue of 'additionality' or how loans are booked.
France should change its position to become as progressive for these deposits as the others.
Hope is therefore being put in the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciuo-Morizet, who will come to Cancun next week.
France's surprise fast-track announcement and its vision for "additional" and the use of loans could trigger an increase in the level of international confidence, necessary to move forward in discussions.
A pesticide-related alarm that children ingest.
A 10-year-old child will be devoured one day by 81 different chemicals, according to one study published this Wednesday, by the Future Generations Association (ex-Movement for Rights and Conservation of Future Generations).
The Association, which points out that its results "do not have a significant statistical value in view of the low number of samples analysed, but are characteristic of the processed issue," bought between July and September foods commonly consumed in four meals and one light meal as a light-hearted snack per child of roughly 10 years in supermarkets in l'Oise and Paris.
These typical dishes, including official recommendations - five pieces of fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 litres of water a day - as well as confectionery,they were analysed by research laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other polluting agents.
The plate's balance is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are carcinogenic, possible or likely, and five substances are among the clear carcinogenic substances, as well as 37 substances that could act as disruptive to internal excrement glands (PEs), according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
"While in almost all cases the legal limits for each chemical admitted individually are not exceeded, in our research we can see well that the reality in the exposure of consumers to contaminating substances, possibly carcinogenic, and/or PE is striking," the association says.
For breakfast, butter and tea with milk contain about ten résidu, with possible carcinogenic effects, and three proven to be shown as certain carcinogens, as is the case with about 20 residues that could disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, reported by the study as a small snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including a banned fungicidal agent in France.
The same goes for the green beans of Kenya, included in lunch, where studios have discovered traces of strong insecticides banned in the EU.
In addition, minced meat steak, tuna in a can, and even a bun and chewing gum were riddled with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the water from the tap, the analysis revealed the presence of nitrate and chloroform.
The salmon's steak for dinner was "richest" with 34 discovered chemical residues, and even the analysis of the plastic plate used to heat meals in the microwave did not avoid analysis.
The final risk for consumers of this "contaminant coke shell" is likely underestimated," the study shows.
The Association of Ecological Europe-Greens (EE-LV) proposed "facilitating to the emergency" to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop the "increase of civilisation diseases."
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) examined the residue status of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereal.
